---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
import MapLink from '../../components/MapLink.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Where to Stay in Bermuda — The Curated Guide"
  description="The best hotels in Bermuda: Rosewood Tucker's Point, The Reefs, Cambridge Beaches, Hamilton Princess, and more. Honest reviews, real booking advice, and timing guidance."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero" style="padding-block: var(--space-16);">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/visit" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Visiting</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Where to Stay</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Where to Stay in Bermuda</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Bermuda's accommodation inventory is smaller than most visitors expect, and
        peak-season dates sell out earlier than they should. Here is the honest guide
        to where to stay and when to book it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- Capacity warning -->
      <div class="alert alert-warning" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <strong>Book early.</strong> Bermuda's hotel inventory is running at approximately 75%
        of its 2019 capacity — several properties have closed permanently or remain shut for
        renovation. For popular weeks (Cup Match in late July/August, Bermuda Heroes Weekend
        in June, any holiday weekend), plan to book <strong>three to six months ahead</strong>.
        Rates on the remaining supply are correspondingly firm. This is real advice, not a
        booking-site upsell.
      </div>

      <!-- Where to stay by location -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Location guide: which parish suits you</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          Bermuda is 21 square miles. No hotel is more than 45 minutes from any beach by scooter.
          But location still matters — it determines your default rhythms, your transport needs,
          and what you walk out of the door into.
        </p>

        <div class="table-wrapper" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Location</th>
                <th>Character</th>
                <th>Good for</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Hamilton (Pembroke Parish)</strong></td>
                <td>City centre; walkable to restaurants, ferry terminal</td>
                <td>Nightlife, dining, day trips in all directions</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Southampton / Warwick</strong></td>
                <td>South shore beach corridor</td>
                <td>Beach focus; close to Horseshoe Bay; south shore trail</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Tucker's Town / Hamilton Parish (East)</strong></td>
                <td>Quiet, exclusive; east side of island</td>
                <td>Privacy, Mid Ocean Club golf, Rosewood property</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Sandy's Parish (West End / Dockyard)</strong></td>
                <td>Remote western tip; access to Great Sound</td>
                <td>Cambridge Beaches; sailing; quiet; ferry to Hamilton</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Paget / Devonshire</strong></td>
                <td>Mid-island; residential feel</td>
                <td>Elbow Beach; 10-minute ferry to Hamilton</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>St. George's Parish (East)</strong></td>
                <td>Historic; quieter; near UNESCO town</td>
                <td>History-focused trips; Tobacco Bay snorkelling</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Luxury tier -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Luxury</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Top of the island</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);">Rosewood Tucker's Point</h3>
          <MapLink query="Rosewood Tucker's Point, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Tucker's Town, Hamilton Parish — east side
          </p>
          <p>
            Rosewood Tucker's Point is the most complete luxury property on the island. It sits
            on a private peninsula in Tucker's Town on the east side — a secluded 200-acre setting
            with its own beach club on Castle Harbour, a golf course, tennis, a spa, and multiple
            restaurants. The rooms are large, the service is attentive without being overbearing,
            and the grounds are genuinely beautiful.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is the property for guests who want a self-contained resort experience rather
            than a base for exploration. You could spend a week here and never need to leave —
            though that would be a waste of Bermuda. The east-side location is quiet and private
            but adds 20–25 minutes to Hamilton and the main ferry routes.
          </p>
          <p>
            Access to the Mid Ocean Club (one of the world's great golf courses) is available
            to hotel guests on select days — a significant draw for golfers. Nightly rates start
            around $700 in peak season; suites considerably more.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
            Prices correct at time of research — verify directly with the property before booking.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-featured" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Cliffside setting</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);">The Reefs Resort &amp; Club</h3>
          <MapLink query="The Reefs Resort and Club, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Southampton Parish — south shore
          </p>
          <p>
            The Reefs occupies a stretch of cliff on Bermuda's south shore in Southampton, with
            rooms and cottages terraced down to a private pink-sand beach. The setting is
            exceptional — the cliffside location means most rooms have genuine Atlantic views,
            and the private beach is small enough to feel uncrowded.
          </p>
          <p>
            It is a smaller property than Tucker's Point — more intimate, less resort-complex. The
            dining (La Serena) is among the better hotel restaurants on the island. The Reefs is
            the choice for guests who want the luxury level without the full resort apparatus. It
            sits close to Horseshoe Bay, making south shore beach access easy.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-featured" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Cottage colony</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);">Cambridge Beaches</h3>
          <MapLink query="Cambridge Beaches, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Sandy's Parish (Somerset) — western tip
          </p>
          <p>
            Cambridge Beaches is a cottage colony — Bermuda's traditional accommodation format,
            distinct from resort hotels. The concept is a collection of private cottages spread
            across landscaped grounds, sharing central facilities (pool, beach, restaurant, spa)
            but offering genuine privacy and an unhurried pace. Cambridge Beaches occupies a
            private peninsula at the western tip of the island with five small private beaches
            on the protected waters of the Great Sound and Mangrove Bay.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is the quietest of the top-tier properties. The pace is deliberately slow.
            Hamilton is a 30-minute ferry ride, which is an advantage if you like the idea of
            being connected to the city but don't want to be in it. The west-end location puts
            you close to the Dockyard and the America's Cup sailing legacy.
          </p>
          <p>
            The cottage colony format is genuinely Bermudian in a way that international branded
            luxury hotels are not. If that matters to you, Cambridge Beaches is the choice.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <!-- Upscale tier -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Upscale</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">The social hub</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);">Hamilton Princess &amp; Beach Club</h3>
          <MapLink query="Hamilton Princess and Beach Club, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Hamilton, Pembroke Parish — city centre, on the harbour
          </p>
          <p>
            The Hamilton Princess — the Pink Hotel — is Bermuda's most socially central property.
            It sits on Hamilton Harbour in the city, and its pool terrace, restaurants, and bar
            areas are where visitors and Bermudians mix in a way that most resort properties
            don't allow for. If you want to be where things are happening, this is the address.
          </p>
          <p>
            The hotel has a long history — it opened in 1885, hosted Allied intelligence operations
            during World War II, and has operated continuously as the island's prestige in-town
            hotel. The current owners (Fairmont) have invested heavily in the property; it is
            well run by current standards, not coasting on history.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Beach Club is a separate facility at Sinky Bay in Southampton — hotel guests
            are ferried there on a private boat. It adds a beach component that the city location
            otherwise lacks. The combination of city convenience and beach access makes this the
            most versatile upscale option on the island for guests who want to see and do a
            lot rather than retreat to a quiet peninsula.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);">Elbow Beach Bermuda</h3>
          <MapLink query="Elbow Beach Bermuda, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Paget Parish — south shore, 10 minutes from Hamilton by ferry
          </p>
          <p>
            Elbow Beach sits on one of the calmer stretches of south shore beach in Paget —
            the water in the bay is notably gentler than Horseshoe or Warwick, making it a
            good choice for families with young children. The hotel is large by Bermuda standards,
            with a range of room categories, multiple pools, and the beachside Mickey's Bistro.
          </p>
          <p>
            The ferry from the Elbow Beach dock to Hamilton takes about 10 minutes, which makes
            it easy to access the city without needing a scooter or taxi for every trip. The
            south shore location gives you beach convenience without the isolation of the western
            or eastern properties.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <!-- Mid-range -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Mid-range</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);">Grotto Bay Beach Resort</h3>
          <MapLink query="Grotto Bay Beach Resort, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Hamilton Parish — north shore, near Crystal Caves
          </p>
          <p>
            Grotto Bay is on the north shore in Hamilton Parish — a different atmosphere from
            the south shore hotels. The resort sits above a sheltered bay with good water access,
            and the grounds include natural caves accessible to guests. It is a mid-range property
            in Bermuda terms, which still means meaningful rates, but it offers real value compared
            to the luxury tier.
          </p>
          <p>
            The north shore location puts you near Crystal Caves (worth a visit in their own right),
            Flatts Inlet (good for kayaking), and the Bailey's Bay/Swizzle Inn area. The airport
            is about 10 minutes away. Not ideal for guests whose priority is south shore beaches,
            but a sensible choice for those focused on water activities and the eastern parishes.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);">Rosemont Guest Suites</h3>
          <MapLink query="Rosemont Guest Suites, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Pembroke — 10 minutes walk from Hamilton city centre
          </p>
          <p>
            Rosemont is a guest suite property rather than a hotel — self-catering units in a
            quiet residential area close to Hamilton. It is a practical choice for independent
            travellers and longer stays: the suite format with kitchen facilities reduces food
            costs meaningfully, and the walkability to Hamilton is a genuine advantage. No resort
            amenities, no pool, no restaurant — the trade-off is direct access to the city's
            dining and waterfront without the premium of a harbour-view hotel room.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <!-- Budget / guesthouses -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Budget and guesthouses</h2>

        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-5);">
          Budget accommodation in Bermuda is limited and should be approached with honesty
          about what it means in this context. The cheapest options on the island start at
          around $150–200 per night for a basic guestroom, which is what mid-range travel
          looks like elsewhere. There is no hostel infrastructure. Vacation rental platforms
          (Airbnb, VRBO) have some inventory, particularly in residential parishes, but
          availability and quality are variable.
        </p>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Edgehill Manor</h3>
          <MapLink query="Edgehill Manor, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Pembroke — near Hamilton</p>
          <p style="margin: 0;">
            A small guesthouse on a hill above Hamilton — clean, simple, and well located. It is
            the most cited budget option in Hamilton Parish. Not a hotel experience; it is a
            guesthouse. The advantage is price and proximity to the city.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Aunt Nea's Inn</h3>
          <MapLink query="Aunt Nea's Inn, Bermuda" />
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">St. George's</p>
          <p style="margin: 0;">
            A small inn in historic St. George's, within walking distance of the UNESCO town
            and a short taxi ride from Tobacco Bay. Good choice for travellers who want to
            spend significant time in the east end and want a quieter, more personal property
            than a large resort.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
          Budget option availability and pricing can change significantly. Verify availability
          directly and read recent reviews before booking.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Booking section -->
      <section style="background-color: var(--color-sand); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Booking and timing advice</h2>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">When to book</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-5);">
          Bermuda's accommodation supply is running at roughly 75% of its pre-pandemic capacity.
          Several formerly significant properties are closed or operating under reduced inventory.
          The consequence is that demand meets a constrained supply — and in peak periods, popular
          properties sell out months ahead.
        </p>
        <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <li><strong>Cup Match weekend (late July/early August):</strong> Book 4–6 months ahead. This is the tightest weekend on the calendar.</li>
          <li><strong>Bermuda Heroes Weekend (mid-June):</strong> Book 3–4 months ahead. Now draws dedicated visitors from outside the island.</li>
          <li><strong>General summer (June–September):</strong> Book 2–3 months ahead for reliable options. Budget for higher rates.</li>
          <li><strong>Shoulder season (April–May, October):</strong> More flexibility — 4–6 weeks is usually sufficient, but the best properties still go quickly.</li>
          <li><strong>Winter (November–March):</strong> Rates drop and availability is easier, though some resort facilities operate reduced hours. The island is quiet; the weather is mild but not beach weather.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Where to book</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          Booking.com has the most complete Bermuda inventory of any aggregator and is the
          easiest way to compare availability and pricing across multiple properties at once.
          Always check the hotel's own website for direct rates — some properties offer better
          rates or added amenities for direct bookings.
        </p>
        <div>
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/go/hotels-bermuda" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn btn-primary">
            Search Bermuda Hotels on Booking.com →
          </a>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-muted); margin-top: var(--space-1);">
            [PLACEHOLDER affiliate link — real ID to be set in affiliate-links.ts after approval]
          </p>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-muted); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          Pilot.BM earns a small commission on bookings made through the link above via the
          Commission Junction / Awin affiliate programme at no extra cost to you. See our
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/legal/affiliate-disclosure">affiliate disclosure</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Practical notes -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Practical notes</h2>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Resort fees and taxes</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-5);">
          Bermuda charges a hotel occupancy tax (currently 9.75%) on top of the room rate.
          Most larger properties also charge a resort fee covering amenities — typically $30–50
          per night — which may or may not be shown upfront in the listed rate. Factor both
          into your budget calculation. A room listed at $400 per night can easily land at
          $475+ after taxes and resort fees.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Scooter vs. car</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-5);">
          No rental cars are available to visitors in Bermuda — this is a long-standing local
          policy to manage road congestion. Options are scooters (available from age 16, most
          hotels can arrange), electric minicars (small, slow, one passenger plus driver),
          buses, ferries, and taxis. Your hotel's location affects how often you need a scooter.
          Hamilton Princess guests can walk to most of the city; Rosewood Tucker's Point guests
          will need transport for almost everything. See the
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/getting-around">Getting Around guide</a> for full detail.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Cancellation policies</h3>
        <p>
          Bermuda hotel cancellation policies are typically stricter than US hotels. Many
          properties require full prepayment for peak-season bookings or charge penalties for
          cancellation within 30–60 days of arrival. Read the cancellation terms carefully
          before booking. Travel insurance is worth considering, particularly for the higher
          nightly rates that Bermuda commands.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="alert alert-info">
        <strong>More planning resources:</strong> The <a href="/Pilot.BM/directory">Pilot.BM directory</a>
        lists current transport operators, taxi services, and scooter rental companies to help
        with logistics once you've chosen your property.
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
